results.notes: Found singly in a pine barren, one foot from the base of Pinus taeda. Cap is 50 mm wide by 40mm tall, globose, tacky to the touch, salmon to orange, fading to light peach towards the margin. Powdery yellow velar remnants crowded towards the margin and creating a fringe on the margin, sparse towards the apex, no staining or bruising when cut. The gills are white, thin and crowded with free attachment, absent of short gills. The stipe is 120mm tall, 20mm wide at the apex, 30mm wide at the base, not elongating with subglobose base, striate, bruising brown an hour after handling, tacky and no staining when cut. There is no distinct aroma

Photos of cystidia are labeled “KOH” or “CR” for Congo red.
Some of the cystidia may be other than hymenial, as the piece of tissue smash-mounted may have included some pileipellis and/or stipe apex.

results.notes:
A perplexing Hygrocybe that seems to shift colors with the environment. When observed in a semi-dry state the next day, the pileus was dark maroon and the gill edge even appeared green! Looking at other photos of H. prieta with the more typically green hymenium and dark pileus, I am convinced it is that. It is possible that the fresh specimens like this one are more brightly pigmented, or it could be a color variety or just a closely related taxon. Microscopically the dimorphic spores fit the measurements of H. prieta in Lodge (1990) and it keys out to this taxon. H. naranjana is discussed as a taxon that closely resembles H. prieta, and the colors of the dry specimen match the illustration in Dennis (1970) almost perfectly. I would not be surprised if they are synonymous.

results.notes:
Growing abundantly in mossy Picea rubens needle litter at the edge of the Whispering Spruce trail. Caps white (2.5Y 8/0 in Munsell); dry; smooth; translucent-striate; up to 9.8 mm wide and 6.3 mm tall. Gills white (2.5Y 8/0); adnate to long-decurrent; margins even; occasionally forked or anastomosing; with 1 to 2 tiers of lamellae. Stems white (2.5Y 8/0); smooth; even; with sparse white basal mycelium; stuffed or occasionally hollow; not releasing liquid when cut; up to 42.1 mm long and 1.1 mm wide. Spore print white. Odor and taste not distinctive. Not fluorescing under UV. Not bioluminescent. Pileipellis composed of hyaline hyphae with diverticulate excrescences. Lamellar trama inamyloid. Pleurocystidia apparently absent. Cheilocystidia scattered; hyaline; smooth; thin-walled; fusiform. Basidia 4-sterigmate. Spores inamyloid, hyaline, smooth, thin-walled and cylindrical. Spore measurements: (6.2) 6.5 – 8.6 (9.6) × (2) 2.2 – 2.9 (3.4) µm; Q = (2.3) 2.7 – 3.3 (3.7); N = 30; Me = 7.6 × 2.5 µm; Qe = 3.1

Margins of cap typically remaining decurved and almost always with at least some of the white velar material adhering in age.

Stems irregular in shape, but begin a clean creamy white, and generally where short and chubby.
Probably Ponderosa Pine-associated, but a variety of trees near fruitings. Coast Live Oak and Madrone usually also present. Also growing near: tan oak, Douglas-fir, manzanitas, possibly other pines.
Sometimes mushrooms in large clumps/clusters.
Stipe, cap, pores and context do not bruise or change color based on exposure, and only the cap really browns ever.
Odor: indistinct, maybe subtly pleasant
Taste: mild, but occasionally sour.
